servicecodeinfo
===============

This C program analyzes one or more service codes (see RFC 4340), provided
numerically or as strings, and prints their allocation classes.

Sample usage
============

% ./servicecodeinfo
Usage: servicecodeinfo NUMBER [NUMBER...]
   or: servicecodeinfo -n NAME [NAME...]
% ./servicecodeinfo 5 1717858426 0x48545450
Service Code           ASCII   Allocation Policy
---------------------- -----   ---------------------------------
5                              First Come First Serve (FCFS)
1717858426             fdpz    First Come First Serve (FCFS)
1213486160             HTTP    Specification Required
% ./servicecodeinfo -n fdpz RA
Service Code           ASCII   Allocation Policy
---------------------- -----   ---------------------------------
1717858426             fdpz    First Come First Serve (FCFS)
1379999776             RA      Specification Required

Changelog
=========

2005-08-30 - Original program provided by Eddie Kohler <kohler@cs.ucla.edu>
2013-09-17 - Converted into buildable package for posting and easy compilation
             by Kim Davies <kim.davies@icann.org>

It looks like you’ve pasted the README-style description of a small C utility called servicecodeinfo. Let me break down what it does and how you can actually use or build it 👇

🔍 What this program does
servicecodeinfo analyzes DCCP Service Codes (from RFC 4340) and tells you:

The numeric value of the service code

Its ASCII representation (if applicable)

The allocation policy (e.g., FCFS, Specification Required)

DCCP (Datagram Congestion Control Protocol) uses these service codes to identify application-level services.

🧠 Key concept
Service codes are 32-bit values that can be:

Entered as numbers (5, 1717858426)

Entered as ASCII strings (HTTP, fdpz)

The tool converts between them and shows how they’re classified.

⚙️ How to compile it
If you have the .c file (e.g., servicecodeinfo.c), compile with:

gcc -o servicecodeinfo servicecodeinfo.c
▶️ How to run it
1. Using numeric service codes:
./servicecodeinfo 5 1717858426 0x48545450
2. Using ASCII names:
./servicecodeinfo -n fdpz RA
📊 Example output explained
Service Code           ASCII   Allocation Policy
---------------------- -----   ---------------------------------
1213486160             HTTP    Specification Required
1213486160 → numeric representation

HTTP → ASCII interpretation

Specification Required → policy defined by IANA

🧾 Allocation policies (quick meaning)
Policy	Meaning
FCFS (First Come First Serve)	Anyone can register it
Specification Required	Needs documented specification
Private / Reserved	Not publicly assignable
🧩 When this is useful
Working with low-level networking (DCCP)

Debugging or analyzing protocol traffic

Studying IANA service code assignments

⚠️ Reality check
DCCP is rarely used in modern systems, so unless you're working on:

kernel/network stack development

academic research

legacy systems

…you probably won’t encounter these often.

