Write a readme for GitHub without using pretty print 

Here’s a clean, GitHub-ready README written in plain Markdown (no “pretty print” blocks or extra formatting tricks):

servicecodeinfo
servicecodeinfo is a small C utility that analyzes DCCP service codes (as defined in RFC 4340) and displays their ASCII representation along with their allocation policy.

Overview
DCCP service codes are 32-bit identifiers used to indicate application-level services. These codes can be represented either as numeric values or as ASCII strings.

This tool allows you to:

Input service codes as numbers or names

Convert between numeric and ASCII representations

Identify the allocation policy associated with each code

Features
Accepts decimal and hexadecimal numeric inputs

Accepts ASCII service code names

Displays allocation policy (e.g., FCFS, Specification Required)

Simple and portable C implementation

Requirements
C compiler (e.g., gcc or clang)

POSIX-compatible system recommended (Linux, macOS, etc.)

Compilation
Compile the program using:

gcc -o servicecodeinfo servicecodeinfo.c

Usage
Run the program with numeric service codes:

./servicecodeinfo NUMBER [NUMBER...]

Or use the -n flag to specify ASCII names:

./servicecodeinfo -n NAME [NAME...]

Examples
./servicecodeinfo 5 1717858426 0x48545450

./servicecodeinfo -n fdpz RA

Output
The program prints a table with the following columns:

Service Code (numeric value)

ASCII representation (if applicable)

Allocation Policy

Example output:

Service Code ASCII Allocation Policy

5 First Come First Serve (FCFS)
1717858426 fdpz First Come First Serve (FCFS)
1213486160 HTTP Specification Required

Allocation Policies
First Come First Serve (FCFS): Open registration

Specification Required: Requires formal documentation

Reserved or Private: Not available for public use

Background
DCCP (Datagram Congestion Control Protocol) is a transport protocol designed for applications that require congestion control without reliable delivery. Service codes are used during connection setup to identify the intended service.

